{
  "doc_id": "44580",
  "text": "A sampling unit is a single linear spatial sensor [CITATION_1] that is completely described by giving its weighting function (receptive-field shape) and position. We allow both real-valued and complex-valued weighting functions. If a sampling unit has a real-valued weighting function it can be thought of as a single neural unit (e.g., a receptor or a simple cell). If a sampling unit has a complex-valued weighting function then it can be thought of as a pair of neural units, one for the real part and one for the imaginary part. For example, a pair of even-and odd-symmetric simple cells located at the same position can be regarded as a sampling unit with a complex weighting function.",
  "correct_citation": {
